{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"acc0c6c4-eb33-4b84-80bc-eb3e300e3fc4","content":"For a .NET Web API, use the `dotnet new webapi` template. Authentication options include:\n\n| Option | Flag |\n|---|---|\n| None (default) | `--auth None` |\n| Individual accounts | `--auth Individual` |\n| Azure AD (work/school) | `--auth SingleOrg` |\n| Azure AD (multi-tenant) | `--auth MultiOrg` |\n| Windows auth | `--auth Windows` |\n\n**Examples:**\n\n```bash\n# API with JWT bearer (Individual accounts)\ndotnet new webapi --auth Individual -o MyApi\n\n# API with Azure AD\ndotnet new webapi --auth SingleOrg --client-id <id> -o MyApi\n```\n\nRun `dotnet new webapi --help` to see all options including `--use-controllers`, `--use-minimal-apis`, and OpenAPI support flags.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"44c9d5db-5043-40ca-969e-21cacf8692a2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about web API project templates and authentication options. This is a general knowledge question about .NET (likely, given the repository context). I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to explore the codebase.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer about dotnet web API templates and authentication options.","outputTokens":283,"requestId":"FC03:903FB:17D4FEB:1AF26B5:69FE8500"},"id":"b7cd4660-4130-45c2-994b-41f8da6e7414","timestamp":"2026-05-09T00:51:19.025Z","parentId":"adb88ef7-1ec5-4d6e-a7dd-d7190c896f8e"}
